ars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Néville I was born in 1187, in Dewsbury, Yorkshire, England, his father, Walter de Néville, was 57 and his mother, Cecily de Crèvecoeur, was 27. He married Margaret de Redbourne. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1219, in Redbourne, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1187–1219":"1187–1219","1178–1250":"1178–1250","1180–1261":"1180–1261","1200–1227":"1200–1227","1210–1249":"1210–1249","1215–1284":"1215–1284","1217–1227":"1217–1227","1131–1198":"1131–1198","1161–1254":"1161–1254","1187":"1187","1198":"1198","Abt 1215":"1215","1131":"1131","1284":"1284","1261":